data.content:
Yes — two improvements depending on your needs:

**1. Simplest: use `[DataRow]` for inline constant data:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

No property needed — cleaner and type-checked at compile time.

**2. For complex/non-constant data, use tuples with `DynamicData`:**

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<object[]> TestData =>
[
    ["valid@email.com", true],
    // ...
];
```

becomes:

```csharp
public static TheoryData<string, bool> TestData => new()
{
    { "valid@email.com", true },
    { "invalid", false },
    { "", false },
};
```

> **Note:** `TheoryData<T1, T2>` requires **MSTest 3.7+** (or xUnit). It gives you generic type safety so you can't accidentally pass an `int` where a `string` is expected.

**TL;DR:** Use `[DataRow]` for simple constants (your case). Use `TheoryData<>` when data is dynamic or complex. Avoid raw `object[]` — it loses type safety and gives poor error messages.
